	<article class="article ">
		<header class="block-content block-content-l1 block-content-center">
						<div class="block-content-header">
				<h6 class="b-content-section heading-square"><a href="/sections/essays-memoirs-true-stories">Essays, Memoirs, and True Stories</a></h6>
				<h1 class="block-content-title">Catching Up</h1>

				
				<ul class="block-content-meta list-inline-border tiny"><li>
							By <a class="meta-article-contributors" href="/contributors/sy-safransky">Sy Safransky</a></li><li><a href="/issues/185">April 1991</a></li></ul>

			</div>

								</header>

				<div class="article-body link-text-wrap">
																		<p>I&rsquo;m never going to read them all. My wife knows it. My children know it. They exchange sly smiles when I haul a big box of magazines along on family vacations. Or when I announce at the beginning of the new year, as fervently as the president promising a balanced budget, that I&rsquo;m finally going to get caught up. They know I&rsquo;ll subscribe to more magazines, that the stack of unread issues &mdash; already taller than I am &mdash; will grow taller still.</p>

<p>I covet magazines, and the time it takes to read them. But there&rsquo;s no way for me to keep up with all the publications I want to read, or should read, or think I should read. I try to keep up, but I can&rsquo;t even keep up with the small changes around me &mdash; a loved one&rsquo;s latest uncertainty, a leaky faucet in the bathroom downstairs.</p>

<p>&ldquo;Words, words,&rdquo; Robert Creeley writes, &ldquo;as if all worlds were there.&rdquo; What a peculiar kind of consumerism &mdash; not of cars and clothes but of ideas and the well-turned phrase. Politics and book&nbsp;reviews and interviews. Spiritual gossip. New lies and old. Some of the magazines I read are well known. Others are &ldquo;alternative&rdquo; &mdash; too cranky, too quirky, too irreverent to have wide appeal. I love all of them, the feel of them; even the glossies, even the ads. I&rsquo;m amazed at the alchemy that turns a stack of manuscripts into a magazine, with a personality no less distinct, no less endearing, than that of a friend.</p>

<p>Yet I&rsquo;ve started to cut back, cancel subscriptions, acknowledge my limitations. We may be limitless in spirit, but there are only so many hours in a day. To admit this is poignant; the heroic ego loves challenges, wants to take on all comers. But I&rsquo;d rather move through life not dragging so many possibilities behind me &mdash; unread magazines, unfinished projects, dreams that wind around other dreams but never take shape. Time, that tease: it croons to you from tomorrow, but doesn&rsquo;t wait for you there.</p>

<p>I&rsquo;ve wondered, too, whether nibbling on magazines doesn&rsquo;t spoil my appetite for a different kind of reading. It&rsquo;s been years since I&rsquo;ve skipped an issue of <em>Harper&rsquo;s</em> or <em>The Nation</em> or <em>The Village Voice</em> or <em>Parabola</em> or <em>New Options</em> or <em>Common Boundary</em> or <em>The New Yorker</em> or <em>Utne Reader</em> or <em>Whole Earth Review</em> &mdash; but it&rsquo;s been even longer since I&rsquo;ve read a line of Shakespeare. When I fell in love with my first wife, more than twenty-five years ago, I set aside James Joyce&rsquo;s <em>Ulysses</em>, intending to get back to it. I&rsquo;m on my third marriage. The book sits on the shelf, unread.</p>

<p>Perhaps I believe too blindly in the redemptive power of reading. All my life, I&rsquo;ve imagined that by reading just a few pages more I can trick truth from its high domain, wrestle it down to earth and make it mine. But such a belief puts too much emphasis on everything I haven&rsquo;t read and don&rsquo;t understand &mdash; and leaves me feeling small. It doesn&rsquo;t acknowledge the great wisdom of the body, the wordless understanding of the heart.</p>

<p>I don&rsquo;t want to feel so overwhelmed that instead of being here now I&rsquo;m always wishing I was <em>there, then</em> &mdash; like an impatient kid counting how many pages are left in a book he needs to finish. I want the words I&rsquo;ll never read to feel not like a burden but a gift, innumerable as the stars and just as mysterious, shining no less brightly for lighting someone else&rsquo;s way.</p>
														</div>


				
