			<div class="article-correspondence layout-item fill-pattern-light">
		<div class="layout-item-intro">
			<h2>Correspondence</h2>
			<a class="xsmall link-alt" href="https://www.thesunmagazine.org/letter-to-the-editor">Write a Letter to the Editor&nbsp;&#9656;</a>
		</div>

		<div id="article-correspondences" class="correspondences correspondences-collapsed">
								<div class="block-correspondence" id="3351">
		<blockquote class="quote-2">
			<p>Sy&rsquo;s piece &ldquo;<a href="/article/1036/">Catching Up</a>&rdquo; [Issue 185] really struck home.</p>

<p>I&rsquo;m (also) a magazine and bookaholic. I&rsquo;ve got the same feelings you put so eloquently: those unread magazines and books can be like a ball and chain. Magazines do &ldquo;spoil&rdquo; appetites. They fit too comfortably into our fast-food lifestyles &mdash; always rushing around grabbing bites instead of really taking the time to sit down to a leisurely, balanced meal. <em>Very</em> seductive &mdash; &ldquo;I can get that article read during lunch!&rdquo;</p>

<p>I&rsquo;m struggling very hard to get out of my &ldquo;intellect solves all&rdquo; mode. Sounds like you&rsquo;re experiencing similar feelings. For me, there&rsquo;s still a big, frustrating gap between <em>knowing</em> and <em>doing</em>. Since I&rsquo;ve finally acknowledged that it&rsquo;s there, I&rsquo;m not as frustrated and puzzled; I know what I need to do now.</p>
							<p class="quote-2-author">Bill Taylor<br>Sacramento, California</p>
					</blockquote>
	</div>

								<div class="block-correspondence" id="3352">
		<blockquote class="quote-2">
			<p>Regarding your &ldquo;Catching Up&rdquo; essay, the &ldquo;spiritual gossip&rdquo; of Hesiod and Master Kung, say, are of greater practical spiritual use than anything you&rsquo;ll read in <em>Harper&rsquo;s</em>. A <em>periodical</em> is not expected to be permanent. The world of <em>Ulysses</em> charts greater spiritual seas than does the <em>Village Voice</em>. Without <em>Ulysses</em>, you&rsquo;ll never be truly &ldquo;here now&rdquo; because you remain unread in one of the truly great monuments of Modernism &mdash; and American Lit in this century was born with Modernism. While the magazines make rich, famous writers of people like Brett Easton Ellis, <em>Moby Dick</em> gathers dust in the English Department. And we wonder how we became so spiritually bankrupt.</p>
							<p class="quote-2-author"><a href="/contributors/sam-hamill">Sam Hamill</a><br>Port Townsend, Washington</p>
					</blockquote>
	</div>

					</div>

				<div class="text-center">
			<button class="b b-1 xsmall js-b-readmore-correspondence" data-collapsible="#article-correspondences" data-label="Read More Letters">Read More Letters</button>
		</div>
			</div>
    
		<div class="article-correspondence-cta">
		<div class="cta cta-l1" data-url="https://www.thesunmagazine.org/letter-to-the-editor">
			<div class="cta-intro">
				<h5 class="cta-title alt-ff">Thinking about writing us a letter?</h5>
				<p class="cta-text">Give in to the temptation. We love getting mail. <br><span class="xsmall">(Of course, we reserve the right to edit.)</span></p>
			</div>
			<a href="https://www.thesunmagazine.org/letter-to-the-editor" class="cta-button b b-4 b-padding-tight small" data-label="Write Us A Letter!">Write Us A Letter!</a>
		</div>
	</div>
	

